HEADWORD: Waggery
<hw>Wag"ger*y</hw> <pr>(-g⟦etil⟧r*⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Waggeries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[From
<er>Wag</er>.]</ety> <def>The manner or action of a wag; mischievous
merriment; sportive trick or gayety; good-humored sarcasm; pleasantry;
jocularity; <as>as, the <ex>waggery</ex> of a schoolboy</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A drollery and lurking <qex>waggery</qex> of expression.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waggie</ent>⟦br⟧
